  "prompt": "If a married woman (in the US) commits adultery and gets pregnant, is her husband legally responsible for the child?",
  "response": "In the United States, the legal responsibility for a child born to a married woman generally falls under the presumption of paternity, which means that her husband is presumed to be the legal father of the child. This presumption can be challenged, and the biological father can be established through paternity testing.\n\nIf the husband is not the biological father and wishes to contest his legal responsibility, he would typically need to take legal action to disestablish paternity. This process usually involves DNA testing and a court order. If paternity is successfully disestablished, the biological father can be identified and may be held legally responsible for child support and other parental obligations.\n\nIt's important to consult with a family law attorney to understand the specifics of the law in your state and to navigate the legal process effectively.",
